{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17486621","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17486621"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:39:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:39:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"146"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"146","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/146"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.06,0.64,0.05,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"146"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98478"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"146","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/146"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"146"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80924"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"207"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"4952"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11624"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"864"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2630"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33672"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98478","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/98478"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn intern is called to review a patient who is \u0027creating a disturbance\u0027 at 1am. The patient is a 40-year-old man admitted two days earlier for alcohol-related acute pancreatitis. Currently he is wandering the corridors at a fast pace and refusing to return to bed. He is shaking the locked door of the ward to try to open it, and appears to have a fine bilateral tremor. Verbal de-escalation has been attempted, but this has not had any effect on calming him and he is minimally engaging with questioning. He is scratching his forearms vigorously. His most recent observations from one hour ago showed a regular heart rate of 120/min, blood pressure 144/70mmHg and respiratory rate of 16/min with a 99% oxygen saturation on room air. His bloods from this morning show chronically deranged but stable liver transaminases, lipase of 800 U/L (normal 15 - 60), and a macrocytosis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Restrain the patient to enable intramuscular clonazepam","Call the duty psychiatrist for urgent review","Offer the patient oral lorazepam","Ask the security staff to physically restrain the patient","Offer the patient intramuscular olanzapine"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient is going through acute alcohol withdrawal. He is day two as an inpatient for alcohol related acute pancreatitis. The alcohol withdrawal is suggested by the acute agitation, bilateral tremor and delusional parasitosis as evidenced by him scratching his arms. His vital signs show a tachycardia and hypertension. This patient is at risk of delirium tremens and requires immediate treatment with a benzodiazepine which should be offered orally in the first instance (eg \u003Cstrong\u003Eoral lorazepam\u003C/strong\u003E). Even in the non-engaging patient, treatment should always first be tried via the least restrictive means necessary. If this attempt at de-escalation does not work, other, more active intervention may be required. He should have regular assessments with the alcohol withdrawal scale or Clinical Institute Withdrawal Assessment of Alcohol Scale.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOlanzapine\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate in the setting of alcohol withdrawal and even in cases where it is indicated, it should be offered orally first. \u003Cstrong\u003ERestraining\u003C/strong\u003E the patient should only be used when all other avenues of de-escalation have been attempted and are unsuccessful. Physical restraint carries significant risks including physical injury, psychological trauma, and can potentially worsen agitation. It should be considered a last resort intervention when there is imminent risk of harm to the patient or others, and only implemented by trained staff following appropriate protocols with continuous monitoring. \u003Cstrong\u003ECalling the duty psychiatrist\u003C/strong\u003E is not required. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPast and current opiate use should be clarified, to consider the risk of respiratory suppression with the combination of benzodiazepines and opiates. Intramuscular or intravenous thiamine should be given before review by the usual treating team the next day.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The de-escalation process of dealing with acute states of confusion should start with simple measures, such as offering the patient oral medication."],"references":["Fulde, G., \u0026 Preisz, P. Managing aggressive and violent patients. Australian Prescriber, 34(4), 116-118. 2011. Available from: https://www.nps.org.au/assets/d95dca0c17137842-9839dbd76e01-697120724af35d48ab4c59041c385cb50aedabecb109e5a3606f9c47d476.pdf","Amore M, D\u0027Andrea M, Fagiolini A. Treatment of Agitation With Lorazepam in Clinical Practice: A Systematic Review. Front Psychiatry. 2021 Feb 22;12:628965. doi: 10.3389/fpsyt.2021.628965. PMID: 33692709; PMCID: PMC7937895.","Albrecht B, Staiger PK, Hall K, Miller P, Best D, Lubman DI. Benzodiazepine use and aggressive behaviour: a systematic review. Aust N Z J Psychiatry. 2014 Dec;48(12):1096-114. doi: 10.1177/0004867414548902. Epub 2014 Sep 2. PMID: 25183003."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80924"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"146"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80924","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/80924"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-13T19:50:33+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-13T19:52:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"146"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98478"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGrou